  "prompt": "I am a third year mu engineering student. I have one kt in semester 2 will I get grace?",
  "response": "In India, the rules regarding grace marks and the treatment of \"KT\" (short for \"keeping term,\" which means you have to clear a backlog) can vary significantly from one university to another. As a third-year engineering student with a KT from semester 2, whether you will get grace marks depends on your specific university's regulations.\n\nHere are some steps you can take to find out:\n\n1. **Check Your University's Rules**: Review your university's academic handbook or website for policies on grace marks and handling of backlogs. They usually have detailed information on eligibility criteria for grace marks.\n\n2. **Contact Your Department**: Reach out to your department office or academic advisor. They can provide you with specific guidance based on your situation and the university's current policies.\n\n3. **Examine Previous Cases**: If possible, look at how similar cases have been handled in the past at your institution. This might give you an idea of what to expect.\n\n4. **Prepare for Re-Examination**: Regardless of whether you will receive grace marks, it's wise to prepare to retake the exam to clear your KT. Make use of study materials, past papers, and perhaps consider tutoring if needed.\n\nRemember, policies can change, so the most reliable information will come directly from your educational institution. It's important to address your KT as soon as possible to avoid complications in your academic progression.",
